            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Ohio income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your Ohio state income tax and local
                city/RITA/JEDD income tax using a simplified model of the
                current Ohio tax brackets and standard deduction. It is designed
                for quick planning and comparison, not for filing your return.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Start from your gross income</h3>
              <p>
                You enter your <strong>annual gross income</strong> (wages,
                salary, self-employment, etc.). If you are not sure of your
                exact Ohio taxable income, using gross income gives a reasonable
                first approximation.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Subtract pre-tax deductions</h3>
              <p>Many taxpayers contribute to pre-tax accounts such as:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Traditional 401(k) or 403(b)</li>
                <li>Health Savings Account (HSA)</li>
                <li>Traditional IRA (if deductible)</li>
                <li>Pre-tax health, dental, or vision premiums</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Enter the total of these amounts in
                <strong>Pre-tax deductions</strong>. The calculator subtracts
                them from your gross income to estimate your
                <em>Ohio adjusted income</em>.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Adjusted income = Gross income − Pre-tax deductions
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Apply the Ohio standard deduction</h3>
              <p>
                Ohio provides a standard deduction that depends on your filing
                status. For simplicity, this calculator uses a typical standard
                deduction for each status and subtracts it from your adjusted
                income:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Single</strong>: base standard deduction</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing jointly</strong>: roughly double the
                  single amount
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing separately</strong>: similar to single
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The result is your estimated
                <strong>Ohio taxable income</strong>.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Ohio taxable income = max(0, Adjusted income − Ohio standard
                  deduction)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Ohio state income tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                Ohio is transitioning toward a flatter income tax but still uses
                a bracketed system. In this calculator we model the current
                structure with:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>A 0% bracket for low incomes</li>
                <li>One or more intermediate brackets</li>
                <li>A single top marginal rate applied above a threshold</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator computes your state tax by applying each marginal
                rate only to the portion of income that falls in that bracket.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  State tax = Σ (Income in bracket × bracket rate)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Local Ohio income tax (city, RITA, JEDD)</h3>
              <p>
                Many Ohio municipalities and school districts levy their own
                income taxes, often administered by RITA or local agencies.
                Typical local rates range from about <strong>1% to 3%</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                In this calculator you enter your
                <strong>combined local rate</strong> as a percentage. We then
                apply that rate to your <strong>gross income</strong> to
                estimate local tax:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Local tax ≈ Gross income × (Local rate ÷ 100)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                Some cities tax only work income, some allow credits for tax
                paid to another city, and some have special rules. For exact
                local tax, check your city or RITA/JEDD instructions.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Credits and total tax</h3>
              <p>
                If you expect Ohio tax credits (for example, retirement income
                credit, joint filing credit, or other nonrefundable credits),
                you can enter an approximate
                <strong>Ohio credits</strong> amount. The calculator subtracts
                this from your state tax, but never below zero:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Net state tax = max(0, State tax − Ohio credits)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                Finally, we add net state tax and local tax to get your
                <strong>total Ohio + local income tax</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>7. Effective tax rate and take-home pay</h3>
              <p>
                Your <strong>effective tax rate</strong> is the share of your
                gross income that goes to Ohio state and local income tax:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Effective rate = (Total Ohio + local tax) ÷ Gross income
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                Your estimated <strong>annual take-home pay</strong> (after Ohio
                state and local tax) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Annual take-home ≈ Gross income − Total Ohio + local tax
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                We then divide by your selected pay frequency (annual, monthly,
                bi-weekly, or weekly) to show an approximate
                <strong>per-paycheck take-home</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses a simplified model of Ohio brackets and standard
                  deductions for the current tax year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not calculate federal income tax, FICA (Social Security
                  and Medicare), or other payroll taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle every Ohio deduction or credit (e.g., detailed
                  business income deduction, education credits).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Local tax is modeled as a flat percentage of gross income and
                  does not account for inter-city credits or special rules.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always compare the results with the official tables from the
                <a
                  href="https://tax.ohio.gov/individual"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Ohio Department of Taxation</a
                >
                and consider consulting a tax professional for complex
                situations.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ: Ohio income tax</h2>

              <h3>Does Ohio have a flat income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                Ohio is moving toward a flatter system, but it still uses
                multiple brackets with a single top marginal rate. Lower incomes
                may pay no state income tax, while higher incomes pay the top
                rate only on income above a threshold. Your
                <strong>effective rate</strong> is usually lower than the top
                marginal rate.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Are local city and RITA taxes included in this calculator?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can enter your combined local rate (for example, 2.25%)
                to estimate city, RITA, or JEDD income taxes. The calculator
                then shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Ohio state income tax</li>
                <li>Local income tax</li>
                <li>Total Ohio + local income tax</li>
                <li>Effective tax rate and take-home pay</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Which tax year does this Ohio income tax calculator use?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator is designed for the most recent Ohio income tax
                brackets and standard deductions available for the 2024–2025
                filing seasons. Because Ohio’s legislature can change rates and
                brackets, you should always verify against the latest tables on
                the Ohio Department of Taxation website.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator enough to file my Ohio return?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is for
                <strong>planning and education only</strong>. It does not
                generate official forms, handle every deduction or credit, or
                reflect all local rules. Use it to understand your approximate
                liability, then rely on official forms, software, or a tax
                professional when you file.
              </p>
            </section>
